    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3dfdfd9c_fcf68ead",
        "filename": "build/run_tests.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 107,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-08T23:47:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e The adb I have on my system doesn\u0027t have -n documented in help, though I see it is here... https://developer.android.com/studio/command-line/adb.html Hopefully it\u0027s been around \"forever\" and it\u0027s just not in the tool\u0027s builtin help.\n\nNowhere near “forever” at all. It showed up in Android platform/system/core 7d5860736097 (https://android.googlesource.com/platform/system/core/+/7d586073609723cb2f6ed37de0ad1a7996e621ae for review benefit), which is in 7.0 (N)’s SDK platform-tools version 24 (https://android.googlesource.com/platform/system/core/+log/android-7.0.0_r1/adb/commandline.cpp). “adb --version” will tell you what you have (at least it will for a recent version).\n\nI don’t know if it’s worth trying to support arbitrarily old SDKs. Things in platform-tools like adb do miss out on support for older devices if you don’t update them from time to time. In this case, all -n does is open /dev/null as stdin, which is nearly as easy to do in the Popen constructor, so I’ll just do that.",
      "parentUuid": "353d9c77_b4575bd5",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 107,
        "startChar": 58,
        "endLine": 107,
        "endChar": 61
      },
